                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origDate calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1795">1210 AH (1795
                                CE)</origDate>
                        </origin>
                       
                        <provenance><p>Folio 1a: a black seal and ownership inscriptions(?) in
                            Arabic.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Two years after the manuscript was copied, it passed into the
                            possession of <persName xml:lang="en" role="fmo" key="">Mūsā bin
                                Yūsuf al-Sabāgh</persName>
                            <persName xml:lang="ar">(موسى بن يسوف السباغ)</persName> who added
                            two inscription to this effect, one on the margins on folio 131b
                            dated 12 Muḥarram 1212 AH, and the other on the title page, dated 25
                            Muḥarram 1212 AH (1797 CE).</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Formerly acquired by <persName role="fmo" key="person_793452"
                            >Frederick North, 5th Earl of Guilford (1766-1827)</persName>;
                            see his armorial bookplate on the <locus from="Front_paste-down"
                                >front paste-down</locus> with the numbers 'No. 70' and 'No.
                            87'. North intended to bequeath his library to the Ionian Academy
                            (Ιόνιος Ακαδημία) which he established as a university in 1824;
                            however, the government refused his stipulations. So, his surviving
                            family members retrieved and sold his library through the London
                            firm of Robert Harding Evans (1778–1857) at eight auctions between
                            1828 to 1835, with this volume appearing in the final sale as lot
                            1851. Possibly purchased at the sale by scholar Nathaniel Bland
                            (1803–1865) for his library at Randalls Park,
                            Leatherhead.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Formerly part of the collection of the Persian scholar <persName
                                type="standard" key="person_20108923" role="fmo">Nathaniel Bland
                                (1803-1865)</persName>. See label on back paste-down: Bland No.
                                281.</p></provenance>
                        
                        <provenance><p>Bland’s oriental manuscripts were sold through <persName
                            key="person_5679225" role="bsl">Bernard Quaritch</persName> in
                            1866 to <persName type="standard" key="person_97751058" role="fmo"
                                >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford</persName>; his
                            bookplate on the <locus from="Back_paste-down">back
                                paste-down</locus>: <quote>Bibliotheca Lindesiana
                                    3/K</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Purchased by <name role="dnr" key="person_f6379">
                            <persName type="display">Enriqueta Rylands
                                (1843–1908)</persName>
                            <persName type="standard"> Rylands, Enriqueta,
                                1843–1908</persName></name> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                    when="1901">1901</date> from <name role="fmo"
                                        key="person_9985420">
                                        <persName type="display">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                            Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>
                                        <persName type="standard">Crawford, James Ludovic Lindsay, Earl
                                            of, 1847–1913</persName>
                                    </name>.</p></provenance>
                        <acquisition><p>Purchased by <persName key="person_f6379" role="dnr"
                            change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands</persName> in 1901 from
                            <persName key="person_9985420" role="fmo" change="#prov-markup"
                                >James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford</persName>, for
                            the John Rylands Library.</p>
                            <p>Bequeathed by Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908) in <date
                                calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to <orgName
                                    type="corporation" role="rps"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                                    Library</orgName>.</p></acquisition>
                    </history>
